result.execSummary:
The defendant Cassandra J. Mills was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant appears with SPD Paul Fredrickson.  Melissa Inlow appears for the State. There is joint recommendation of 12 month probation with conditions including treatment/counseling and mental health also if deemed appropriate.  Defendant pleads guilty to Count 1.  Judge reviews charge.  Count 2 to be dismissed and read-in.  Court reviews plea questionnaire/elements/waiver of rights with defendant.  Defense stipulates to factual basis in complaint.  Court finds defendant freely, voluntarily, and intelligently enters her plea and waives her rights  Court finds a factual basis exists and is found guilty of Count 1.  State has complied with victim notifications.  Recommending 1 yr probation with conditions for anger management, mental health eval, and any other treatment/counseling/conditions as recommended by probation agent.  Court accepts the recommendation and orders 1 year probation with the conditions:    The defendant shall comply with any treatment, evaluations and/or programming as deemed appropriate by the COMPAS assessment and the probation agent.  Defendant must sign any releases agent deems necessary to verify defendant's compliance with probation conditions.  The programming is to include anger management, mental health issues, and any other programming probation agent deems appropriate.  Must pay the costs of the action including the DNA surchage and must supply a DNA sample.  Must report to probation today.  Count 2 is dismissed and read-in.
